  "answer": {
    "Problem Formalization": "We seek to recover an unknown source term f(x,y) in the Poisson equation ∇²φ(x,y) = f(x,y) over a 2D domain Ω, given sparse measurements of the potential field φ(x,y) at N_obs observation locations, and Dirichlet or Neumann boundary conditions on ∂Ω. The inverse problem is: minimize ||φ_pred(x_i) - φ_obs(x_i)||² over i∈obs subject to ∇²φ_pred = f_pred, where f_pred is parameterized by a neural network. Missing information: observation noise level, exact boundary condition type, domain geometry (rectangular vs irregular), source regularity (smooth vs singular), and whether f is known to be localized or distributed.",
    "Physics Constraints": "The governing PDE is the Poisson equation: ∂²φ/∂x² + ∂²φ/∂y² = f(x,y). This provides the physics-informed residual R = ∇²φ_NN - f_NN that must be zero everywhere. Boundary conditions on ∂Ω must be enforced (penalty or hard constraint): either φ|∂Ω = g_D (Dirichlet) or ∂φ/∂n|∂Ω = g_N (Neumann), or mixed. If boundary condition type is unspecified, we assume Dirichlet as default but must flag this as a workflow assumption requiring validation. The source f should satisfy integrability constraints if physical (e.g., non-negative for charge sources).",
    "Model Choice": "Use a shared-encoder decoder architecture: one neural network F(x,y; θ_f) outputs the source field f(x,y), and a second network Φ(x,y; θ_φ) outputs the potential φ(x,y). Alternatively, use a single network with two output channels. Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) are appropriate because: (1) the PDE operator is well-defined and differentiable; (2) collocation points can enforce the PDE everywhere in Ω; (3) boundary data can be incorporated as hard or soft constraints. For network architecture, fully connected ResNets or Fourier feature networks are recommended to capture smooth source fields; convolutional encoders if spatial structure is expected. The source network should have sufficient capacity to represent the anticipated complexity of f (spectral bias may require Fourier features for high-frequency components).",
    "Training Strategy": "Minimize composite loss L = λ_data·L_data + λ_pde·L_pde + λ_bc·L_bc + λ_reg·L_reg. (1) L_data = (1/N_obs) Σ||Φ(x_i; θ_φ) - φ_obs(x_i)||² over observation points. (2) L_pde = (1/N_coll) Σ[∇²Φ(x_j) - F(x_j; θ_f)]² over collocation points in Ω. (3) L_bc = (1/N_bc) Σ||B[Φ(x_k)] - g(x_k)||² on boundary points. (4) L_reg = weight decay or explicit smoothness penalty on F to regularize source recovery. Sampling: use Latin hypercube or adaptive sampling favoring high-gradient regions. Optimization: Adam for warm-start, L-BFGS-B for fine-tuning. Weights λ are typically set as λ_pde >> λ_data >> λ_bc (PDE satisfaction prioritized).",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "1. Non-uniqueness: The inverse problem is ill-posed; multiple source distributions can produce the same potential field. Mitigation: add regularization (smoothness, sparsity, or known physical constraints) and validate against hold-out boundary data. 2. PDE satisfaction vs. data fitting trade-off: too strong λ_pde causes field to satisfy PDE but ignore observations; too weak λ_pde allows non-physical solutions. Mitigation: tune λ via validation loss on held-out boundary measurements. 3. Boundary condition ambiguity: if boundary condition type is wrong, reconstructed field will be incorrect everywhere. Mitigation: test both Dirichlet and Neumann assumptions if unknown; use residual on boundary as diagnostic. 4. Noise sensitivity: measurement noise propagates to source recovery, amplified by Laplacian operator. Mitigation: increase regularization strength, use smoothing on observations. 5. Network architecture mismatch: insufficient depth/width fails to capture source complexity; spectral bias prevents high-frequency source recovery. Mitigation: use Fourier feature embeddings; validate with synthetic test cases of varying smoothness. 6. Collocation point deficiency: insufficient sampling in regions with sharp source gradients yields inaccurate PDE residual. Mitigation: adaptive refinement or higher collocation density."
  }
}

